# Sliding Window Maximum (Deque) - SCN Notes

## Concept

For every window of size `k`, find the maximum element.

A **Deque** stores indices of elements in **decreasing order of values**:

* Front of deque stores the index of the maximum element.
* Remove indices that go out of the current window.
* Remove smaller elements from the back before inserting a new element.

---

## Approach

### 1. Process First Window

Build a decreasing deque.

```java
while(!dq.isEmpty() && nums[dq.peekLast()] <= nums[i])
{
    dq.removeLast();
}
dq.addLast(i);
```

Store the maximum of the first window:

```java
res[0] = nums[dq.peekFirst()];
```

---

### 2. Process Remaining Windows

### Remove Outdated Indices

Indices outside the current window cannot contribute to the answer.

```java
while(!dq.isEmpty() && dq.peekFirst() <= i-k)
{
    dq.removeFirst();
}
```

### Remove Smaller Elements

Smaller elements behind the current element can never become maximum.

```java
while(!dq.isEmpty() && nums[dq.peekLast()] <= nums[i])
{
    dq.removeLast();
}
```

### Add Current Index

```java
dq.addLast(i);
```

### Store Window Maximum

```java
res[i-k+1] = nums[dq.peekFirst()];
```

---

## Code

```java
class Solution {
    public int[] maxSlidingWindow(int[] nums, int k) {
        Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
        int res[] = new int[nums.length - k + 1];

        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            while (!dq.isEmpty() && nums[dq.peekLast()] <= nums[i]) {
                dq.removeLast();
            }
            dq.addLast(i);
        }

        res[0] = nums[dq.peekFirst()];

        for (int i = k; i < nums.length; i++) {

            while (!dq.isEmpty() && dq.peekFirst() <= i - k) {
                dq.removeFirst();
            }

            while (!dq.isEmpty() && nums[dq.peekLast()] <= nums[i]) {
                dq.removeLast();
            }

            dq.addLast(i);

            res[i - k + 1] = nums[dq.peekFirst()];
        }

        return res;
    }
}
```

---

## Key Points

* Deque stores **indices**, not values.
* Front always contains the index of the maximum element.
* Remove expired indices from the front.
* Remove smaller elements from the back.
* Each element is inserted and removed at most once.

---

## Complexity

```java
Time  : O(n)
Space : O(k)
```

